Name: PMP *tau-mata 'person, human being'
Comment: Also [Kei](LanguageTable#cldf:298) _umat_, [Kairiru](LanguageTable#cldf:667) _ramat_, [Wogeo](LanguageTable#cldf:19063) _ramata_, [Molima](LanguageTable#cldf:18975) _tomotau_, [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:19079) *_aramata_ ‘person, human being’.  [Dempwolff (1938)](Source#cldf:dempwolff193438) posited *_tau-mataq_ ‘(unripe = not yet dead) living person’, citing an earlier publication by Adriani for the interpretation that the second morphological element in this word is identical to [PAn](LanguageTable#cldf:19072) *_ma-qetaq_ ‘raw, unripe, green (fruit), uncooked’.  However, no known reflex of this form preserves final consonants, leaving this interpretation uncertain.  Whatever this added element was, it contributed nothing discernible to the semantics of the base, as both [Sangir](LanguageTable#cldf:402) and [Proto-Oceanic](LanguageTable#cldf:19082) have reflexes of [PAn](LanguageTable#cldf:19072) *_Cau_ next to the longer form with no difference of meaning.

PMP *isu₂ 'interjection used to chase off animal'
PAN *k-ita 'we (incl.)'
Comment: Also [Fijian](LanguageTable#cldf:266) _keda_ ‘we (plural incl.)’.  Forms that appear to reflect *_i-kita_ have simply incorporated the closely bound personal case marker for first and second person reference (less commonly, some languages have extended a reflex of *_si_, the bound personal case marker for third person reference to the base *_ita_ or *_kita_. Since this was not an affix in [PAn](LanguageTable#cldf:19072) it is not treated as part of morphology here.  It has long been known that first person plural pronouns have two distinct shapes (*_ami_/_kami_, *_ita_/_kita_), but both the morphology and the semantics that distinguish these pairs have remained elusive.  Some languages have _k_-initial forms for all non-third person forms, as with [Amis](LanguageTable#cldf:227) _kako_ ‘I’, _kiso_ ‘you’, _ciŋra_ ~ _ciira_ ‘s/he’, _kita_ ‘we (incl.)’, _kami_ ‘we (excl.)’, _kamo_ ‘you (pl.)’, _caŋra_ ~ _caira_ ‘they’.  Others, as [Karo Batak](LanguageTable#cldf:18314) or [Toba Batak](LanguageTable#cldf:427), contrast _k_-initial forms which function as more formal expressions of plural reference, or as polite 2nd sg. reference, with vowel-initial forms which function as familiar or intimate expressions of plural reference, and are not used at all in singular reference.  There is little evidence that the forms *_kita_ and *_kami_ are bimorphemic, and the best option based on present evidence appears to be that vowel-initial and _*k_-initial forms were variants that conveyed distinctions of formality in [PAn](LanguageTable#cldf:19072). Reflexes that are ambiguous for *_ita_ or *_kita_ have been assigned to the latter, since it is somewhat more common than the former.

Comment:
Also [Tagalog](LanguageTable#cldf:423) _duryan_, [Mapun](LanguageTable#cldf:19176) _duyan_, [Binukid](LanguageTable#cldf:19012), [Manobo (Western Bukidnon)](LanguageTable#cldf:819), [Mansaka](LanguageTable#cldf:825) _dolyan_ ‘the durian tree and fruit, _Durio zibethinus_ Murr.’, [Maranao](LanguageTable#cldf:331) _dorian_ ‘durian tree: _Durio zibethinus_ Murr.’, _dorian a amoʔ_ ‘soursop: _Annona muricata muricata_ L.’, [Tiruray](LanguageTable#cldf:433) _duriyan_, [Tausug](LanguageTable#cldf:18831) _dūyan_, [Yakan](LanguageTable#cldf:1129) _duwiʔan_, [Javanese](LanguageTable#cldf:285) _durèn_, [Balinese](LanguageTable#cldf:235) _duryan_ ~ _durén_, [Sasak](LanguageTable#cldf:404) _durian_ ~ _durén_, [Balaesang](LanguageTable#cldf:19201), [Totoli](LanguageTable#cldf:1084) _durian_, [Dampelas](LanguageTable#cldf:18954) _duhian_, Taje _ruriaŋ_, [Uma](LanguageTable#cldf:19170) _duri_, [Bare'e](LanguageTable#cldf:236) _oria_, [Wolio](LanguageTable#cldf:1124) _duria_, [Tae'](LanguageTable#cldf:18947) _durian_, [Mandar](LanguageTable#cldf:813), [Buginese](LanguageTable#cldf:239), [Makassarese](LanguageTable#cldf:325) _duriaŋ_ ‘durian tree and fruit’.  



From *_duRi_ ‘thorn’ + _-an_.  [Malay](LanguageTable#cldf:326) _durian_ does not show the expected neutralization of prepenultimate vowels as schwa, possibly because this form was still perceived as bimorphemic.  A number of reflexes in the Philippines and Sulawesi are best explained as [Malay](LanguageTable#cldf:326) loans, but this is impossible for Tau’t Batu (Palawan) _dugyan_, and for such obviously native forms as [Berawan (Long Terawan)](LanguageTable#cldf:19191) _kəjin_, and [Kiput](LanguageTable#cldf:18958) _ləcin_, which show highly distinctive phonological developments.  The distributional evidence for this form suggests that the durian was first encountered by AN speakers in Palawan or Borneo and at a later date was carried south and east by Malay traders.

PMP *dahun 'leaf; blade of paddle or oar; ‘table’ for eating'
Comment:
Also [Toba Batak](LanguageTable#cldf:427) _daon_ ‘leaf, medicine’, [Arosi](LanguageTable#cldf:485) _rawa_ Also [Toba Batak](LanguageTable#cldf:427) _daon_ ‘leaf, medicine’, [Arosi](LanguageTable#cldf:485) _rawa_ ‘leaf’.  The secondary meaning ‘head hair’ is widespread in the languages of eastern Indonesia and the Pacific, and looks very much like a Papuan contact feature.  Since this apparent innovation is found as far east as Polynesia it probably was acquired by or before Proto-Oceanic times, and then transmitted like any other feature of the language as Austronesian speakers spread eastward beyond the reach of Papuan contact.  The fact that it also appears in Sama-Bajaw languages, but nowhere else in western Indonesia or the Philippines, lends strength to the hypothesis that it is due to Papuan contact, since the Sama-Bajaw almost certainly were involved in the spice trade that linked the Moluccas of eastern Indonesia with various ports in western Indonesia and the southern Philippines, and so would have had many opportunities for contact with Papuan-speaking groups.


In addition, polymorphemic reflexes in [Bikol](LanguageTable#cldf:244), [Iban](LanguageTable#cldf:276), [Malay](LanguageTable#cldf:326), and [Gitua](LanguageTable#cldf:270) suggest that *_dahun_ figured in the name for the whip snake, a small, green poisonous species that presumably is well camouflaged in foliage, and hence extremely dangerous.  Although a specific term cannot be reconstructed on the basis of known evidence, this may have been [PMP](LanguageTable#cldf:19081) *_hulaR dahun_.  The names of various birds ([Iban](LanguageTable#cldf:276), [Malay](LanguageTable#cldf:326), [Sundanese](LanguageTable#cldf:418), Bolaang Mongondow) fish ([Malay](LanguageTable#cldf:326), [Sangir](LanguageTable#cldf:402), [Chamorro](LanguageTable#cldf:573), [Manggarai](LanguageTable#cldf:816), [Fijian](LanguageTable#cldf:266), Kapingamarangi), and insects ([Tombonuwo](LanguageTable#cldf:19188), [Malay](LanguageTable#cldf:326)) that incorporate a reflex of [PMP](LanguageTable#cldf:19081) *_dahun_ may be products of convergence, or retentions of terms for which the surviving evidence is too fragmentary for reconstruction, and the common element in expression such as [Malagasy](LanguageTable#cldf:18432) _daun pintu_ ‘body of door’, [Manggarai](LanguageTable#cldf:816) _sau? para_, [Asilulu](LanguageTable#cldf:18016) _matanulu lau_ ‘door’ probably is the result of historically secondary changes.

Name: POC *manu-manuk 'insect'
Comment: Also [Isneg](LanguageTable#cldf:647) _anúʔ_ ‘the barnyard fowl or chicken’, _an-anúʔ_ ‘a general name for birds’, [Malay](LanguageTable#cldf:326) _manok-manok_ ‘a tree: sp. unident.’, [Karo Batak](LanguageTable#cldf:18314) _anuk-anuk_ ‘bird (generic)’, ['Āre'āre](LanguageTable#cldf:18004) _mānu_ ‘bird, insect, said of anything that flies’.  This semantic history of this form is discussed in [Blust (2002)](Source#cldf:blust2002), where it is noted that [PMP](LanguageTable#cldf:19081) *_manuk_ clearly meant ‘chicken’, and the generic term for ‘bird’ was formed from it by reduplication as *_manuk-manuk_, or possibly *_manu-manuk_.  In [Proto-Oceanic](LanguageTable#cldf:19082), however, *_manuk_ had already shifted its sense from ‘chicken’ to ‘bird’, and the reduplicated form came to mean ‘insect, small flying creatures other than birds’.  Whether the [Basai](LanguageTable#cldf:19171) and [Trobiawan](LanguageTable#cldf:19209) terms in Taiwan are native or loans from a Philippine source during the Spanish occupation of northern Taiwan from 1626 to 1642 remains an open question, although the fact that they mean ‘bird’, while nearly all unreduplicated forms in Philippine languages mean ‘chicken’ supports the view that they are native, and that *_manuk_ can thus be assigned to [PAn](LanguageTable#cldf:19072), presumably in the meaning ‘chicken’ (next to *_qayam_ ‘bird’).

Name: PWMP *maR-manuk 'raise chickens'
Comment: Given its modern implications this form probably is a product of independent development.

Name: PPH *manuk-en '(gloss uncertain)'
Comment: An affixed form *_manuk-en_ can be posited for [Proto-Philippines](LanguageTable#cldf:19083), but it is unclear what this word meant.  Reflexes in [Ilokano](LanguageTable#cldf:279), [Tagalog](LanguageTable#cldf:423)  and [Tausug](LanguageTable#cldf:18831)  evidently derive from the sponsorship and betting that typically take place in cockfighting, but the antiquity of cockfighting in the Austronesian world remains uncertain ([Blust 2002:96-98](Source#cldf:blust2002)).  Reflexes in [Casiguran Dumagat](LanguageTable#cldf:569)  and [Ibaloy](LanguageTable#cldf:19182) suggest what is perhaps an older meaning, namely the taking of omens from the flight of birds or examination of the entrails of chickens.  The meaning ‘crosseyed’, which is shared by [Bikol](LanguageTable#cldf:244) and [Maranao](LanguageTable#cldf:331) is distinct from either of these, but is not sufficiently widely attested to attribute to [Proto-Philippines](LanguageTable#cldf:19083).

Name: POC *i-lima 'five'

Name: PWMP *iŋ-lima 'five times'
Comment: For [Mongondow](LanguageTable#cldf:245) _i-lima_ ‘the fifth’ cp. e.g. [Kadazan Dusun](LanguageTable#cldf:287) _iŋg-onom_, [Malagasy](LanguageTable#cldf:18432) _in-énina_ ‘six times’,[Mongondow](LanguageTable#cldf:245) _iŋg-onon_ ‘the sixth’.  This still poorly understood numeral prefix evidently had different allomorphs before vowel-initial and consonant-initial bases.

Name: PWMP *ka-lima 'five times'
Comment: In many languages it is difficult to disinguish reflexes of this form from reflexes of [PAn](LanguageTable#cldf:19072) *_Sika-lima_ ‘the fifth’.  Both *_ka-lima_ and *_maka-lima_ appear to have meant ‘five times’, and it is therefore possible that the data taken to support this shorter word are actually truncated forms of *_maka-lima_.

Name: PWMP *kuma-lima 'fifth in order'
Comment: Possibly _*k<um>a-lima_ ‘become fifth’.

Name: PAN *maka-lima 'five times'
Comment: [Onvlee (1984)](Source#cldf:onvlee1984) gives [Kambera](LanguageTable#cldf:678) _njara makalimangu baina_ ‘a stallion with five mares’ (lit. ‘a stallion, five times his mares’, but this appears to be _njara ma-ka-lima-ŋu bai-na_ ).  It is possible that the [PAn](LanguageTable#cldf:19072) form meaning ‘five times’ was *_maka-lima-N_.

Name: PWMP *maŋ-lima 'divide into groups of five'
Comment: Although the prefix in this form clearly was _*maŋ-_, it may have had an allomorph [_maŋa_] before bases that began with a liquid consonant.

Name: PAN *qa-lima 'hand'
Comment: This form is puzzling, as it is clearly derived from *_lima_ ‘five’, but *_qa-_ is not a known affix.  A number of other languages reflect *_lima_ as both ‘five’ and ‘hand’, in the latter meaning presumably by reduction of the longer form.  In other cases the two senses are distinguished by stress, as in [Bontok](LanguageTable#cldf:246) _limá_ ‘five’ : _líma_ ‘hand and arm’, or [Kankanaey](LanguageTable#cldf:289) _limá_ ‘five’ : _líma_, _ma-limá-an_ ‘manipulated; rickety, as chickens or dogs that are manipulated too much in their youth’.  The latter meaning raises questions about whether seemingly distinct items such as [Cebuano](LanguageTable#cldf:252) _alíma_ ‘take care of someone by administering to his needs’, or [Manobo (Western Bukidnon)](LanguageTable#cldf:819) _elima_ ‘to care for; to look after; to provide for, as children, plants, garden, animals, etc.’ might also be related (cf. English ‘to handle someone’s affairs’).

Name: PAN *ma-lima-N 'fifty'
Comment: The reconstruction of this pattern for multiples of ten in [PAn](LanguageTable#cldf:19072) was first demonstrated by [Zeitoun, Teng and Ferrell (2010)](bib-Zeitoun).

Name: PPH *paR-lima-en 'divide into five'
Comment: [Puyuma](LanguageTable#cldf:386) ([Tsuchida 1980](Source#cldf:tsuchida1980)) also has a pattern _paR-X-n_ for bases ending in a vowel, and _paR-X-en_ for bases ending in a consonant, meaning ‘to do X times’.  However, for this affixational pattern the innovative form _luwaT_ ‘five’ is used, yielding _paR-luwaT_ ‘to do five times’.  While this form cannot be directly compared with those in Philippine languages, it does suggest that if a reflex of *_lima_ had been retained in this type of construction the result would have been **_paR-lima-n_, and the reconstruction given here would then be upgraded to [PAn](LanguageTable#cldf:19072).

Name: PMP *mata nu bisul 'core of a boil'
PMP *mata nu haŋin 'point of the compass, direction of the wind'
Comment: This complex term clearly referred to the direction of the wind (in sailing).  In [Proto-Polynesian](LanguageTable#cldf:19084) the original morpheme boundary was lost and the adjacent low vowels fused into a single short vowel.  The unanalyzable morpheme _mataŋi_ then came to refer to the wind in general (although the reflex in [Rennellese](LanguageTable#cldf:390) retains the original sense in addition to the general sense of ‘wind’).  [Niue](LanguageTable#cldf:362) _mata mataŋi_ appears to be an attempt to restore the original sense of directionality by repeating _mata_ ‘eye’ as an independent morpheme, since the original morphology has been lost, and with it the specifying property of *_mata_.

Name: PMP *mata nu hikan 'callus on the foot (lit. ‘fish eye’)'

PWMP *mata nu puket 'mesh of a net'
Comment: Also [Cebuano](LanguageTable#cldf:252) _matá sa báliŋ_ ‘mesh of a net’, [Iban](LanguageTable#cldf:276) _mata jala_ ‘meshes added when making a cast-net to increase diameter and produce cone shape’, [Sangir](LanguageTable#cldf:402) _mata-n soma_ ‘mesh of a net’.  The reconstruction with *_puket_ is supported by comparative evidence, but *_mata_ undoubtedly was used with reference to the mesh of nets in general, an association that is also found in languages that belong to other genetic groupings, as Japanese (_ami no me_; net GEN eye), and Hebrew (_ayin ha rέʃεt_).  In some cases it is unclear whether the reference is to the holes in the net or to the knots that give it structure.
